  "report": {
    "narrative": [
      "Within the provided VictoriaMetrics preview for 2026-03-01..2026-03-24, there are no InfiniBand health/error metrics (e.g., port counters, symbol/CRC errors, link down events) and no storage SMART health/failure indicators (e.g., smartctl attributes, reallocated/pending sectors, media errors, critical warnings). Because of that, I cannot credibly identify any specific nodes with abnormal fabric error behavior or SMART failures from this preview alone.\n\nThe only host-scoped hardware signal shown is ROCm GPU temperature for a small subset of nodes (e.g., k002-004-v5/v7/v1/v8/v6 and k002-003), which suggests there is telemetry for some components, but it does not provide fabric/storage degradation evidence. Any attempt to rank fabric/storage risk or separate noise vs. real degradation would be speculative without the relevant counters and SMART attributes.\n\nOperator impact assessment (conditional): if IB error counters or link flaps were present, likely impacts would include degraded multi-node training throughput, intermittent NCCL/MPI timeouts, and job slowdowns; if SMART faults were present, impacts would include elevated job failure rates, filesystem corruption risk, and node drain/maintenance triggers. However, the strength of evidence here is weak-to-none due to missing signals in the preview."
    ],
    "highlights": [
      "Evidence gap: no InfiniBand error/health metrics are included in the preview, so no high-risk fabric nodes can be identified from this data.",
      "Evidence gap: no disk/NVMe SMART health/failure metrics are included in the preview, so no nodes can be flagged for storage degradation from this data.",
      "What is available: 72 hosts are instrumented overall, and ROCm temperature hotspots exist on k002-004-v5/v7/v1/v8/v6 and k002-003, but these do not establish fabric/storage issues.",
      "Recommended to separate noise vs degradation once metrics exist: use rates over time (e.g., increase() / rate()) for IB counters and SMART error deltas; treat single-sample blips as probable noise, persistent growth as meaningful degradation."
    ],
